    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3273820489" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3273820489" />
    <a title="Lizp" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/23737656-lizp"><img alt="Lizp" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/f_50x66-6a03a5c12233c941481992b82eea8d23.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3273820489?book_show_action=true">Apr 10, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lizp" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lizp" href="/user/show/23737656-lizp">Lizp</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3273820489" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16055990868292270600">This is a beautifully written book. I return to it over and over. Toibin’s prose is magical.<br/><br/>Some people didn’t like the judge character, Redmond. I thought he was an interesting and complex character. The book tells the story of Eamon Redmond, an Irish High Court judge. It flashes between his childhood and his later life. He lives in a small Wexford village as a child. Redmond is a staunch member of Fianna Fail. De Valera and Haughey ( both Fianna Fáil leaders) feature in the book.<br/><br/>Early in the b</span>
  <span id="freeText16055990868292270600" style="display:none">This is a beautifully written book. I return to it over and over. Toibin’s prose is magical.<br /><br />Some people didn’t like the judge character, Redmond. I thought he was an interesting and complex character. The book tells the story of Eamon Redmond, an Irish High Court judge. It flashes between his childhood and his later life. He lives in a small Wexford village as a child. Redmond is a staunch member of Fianna Fail. De Valera and Haughey ( both Fianna Fáil leaders) feature in the book.<br /><br />Early in the book, we are exposed to a couple of controversial court judgments Redmond makes. He’s a solitary character and is distant even from his own wife, Carmel. She sometimes challenges him about this, but to no avail. His mum dies when he is very young. It’s hard to work out whether that loss rendered him a distant and solitary person, or whether he was by nature solitary. His young life is beset by death. First he loses his grandad shortly after spending a happy Christmas with him. Shortly afterwards, his Uncle Stephen passes away from TB. His dad tries to comfort him on that loss, but he just can’t bear it and shuts out the comforting gesture.<br /><br />Redmond is a terrible communicator when it comes to emotional issues. As a boy he suffers much embarrassment at being in his dad’s class at school. His dad has a stroke and communication is, of course, even more difficult. As a teenager, his dad’s illness complicates his life just as he becomes political, and also starts to notice girls. He meets Carmel, his future wife. They are both politically active and plan a life together. <br /><br />His single daughter Niamh gets pregnant at a difficult time for him professionally, as at the same time a high profile case involving an unmarried woman who was sacked from her teaching position in a religious school for being pregnant, not married, and living with a married man, the father of her child, is being heard. The issue is whether she should get her job back and be compensated. His son Donal, just like Redmond, can be emotionally distant. Redmond finds it difficult to communicate with both his children. <br /><br />Redmond is eminent in Fianna Fail, now the establishment and conservative. His dad, by way of contrast, was a message carrier for the IRA. The political history is complex and bitter. De Valera (a famous Fianna Fáil leader) forgetting his own origins when he came to power had some of his own ( IRA men) shot.<br /><br />The Catholic Church’s stranglehold on Ireland is well explored. Christ and Caesar ever being hand in glove. Republican ideology is visited. There’s an interesting critique of the development of Ireland as a State. The book contains lyrically beautiful descriptions of the landscape.<br /><br />I highly recommend this wonderfully written book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16055990868292270600" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


