<div id="review_905873858" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/905873858" />
    <a title="Jonathan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8258265-jonathan"><img alt="Jonathan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1590662168p2/8258265.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/905873858?book_show_action=true">Sep 08, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jonathan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jonathan" href="/user/show/8258265-jonathan">Jonathan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8258265-jonathan?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer905873858" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4659694193427339544">I can&apos;t say that this was anywhere near my favourite of Colm Toibin&apos;s novels, however I was visting Dublin for most of the time I was reading it, and as the action moves back and forth between the city and a coastal town it was good to read it for my holiday.<br/><br/>The story is about Eamon, a judge, and his family. He is a bit disconnected from his wife, daughter and son. We learn that this is due to things that happened in his childhood and young adulthood. I also felt a lack of empathy for him (inten</span>
  <span id="freeText4659694193427339544" style="display:none">I can't say that this was anywhere near my favourite of Colm Toibin's novels, however I was visting Dublin for most of the time I was reading it, and as the action moves back and forth between the city and a coastal town it was good to read it for my holiday.<br /><br />The story is about Eamon, a judge, and his family. He is a bit disconnected from his wife, daughter and son. We learn that this is due to things that happened in his childhood and young adulthood. I also felt a lack of empathy for him (intentionally on the part of the author, I am sure), and generally he is a difficult character to like. So why is that? Maybe Toibin is trying to find reasons for men being as they are, especially generations who have seen, and taken part in, the changes that Ireland underwent in the last century. It is easier for him to pass judgement on others than it is to talk about his feelings, or to show that he does care about his family.<br /><br />As it is one of his early books I think he was exploring the idea of family relationships, especially in relation to illnesses, that he would write about more successfully later on. As I say, not his best, but well written of course, and, thankfully, a conclusion that gives us a bit of hope.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4659694193427339544" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


